{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585418"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:11:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:11:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14969"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14969"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0.03,0.03,0.07,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7657"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115416"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7657"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14969"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97419"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"5440"},{"type":"tags","id":"8111"},{"type":"tags","id":"9885"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18724"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18727"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115416"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ELymph nodes are organised structures that filter lymph fluid and facilitate immune responses. Understanding their internal architecture is essential for comprehending immune system function.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following represents the correct path of lymph flow through a lymph node?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Afferent lymphatics\u2192subcapsular space\u2192outer cortex\u2192deep cortex\u2192medullary sinus\u2192efferent lymphatics","Afferent lymphatics\u2192subcapsular space\u2192deep cortex\u2192outer cortex\u2192medullary sinus\u2192efferent lymphatics","Afferent lymphatics\u2192medullary sinus\u2192deep cortex\u2192outer cortex\u2192subcapsular space\u2192efferent lymphatics","Afferent lymphatics\u2192medullary sinus\u2192outer cortex\u2192deep cortex\u2192subcapsular space\u2192efferent lymphatics","Afferent lymphatics\u2192subcapsular space\u2192medullary sinus\u2192outer cortex\u2192deep cortex\u2192efferent lymphatics"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe flow of lymph through a lymph node follows a specific and organised path that maximises exposure to immune cells. \u003Cstrong\u003EAfferent lymphatics\u2192subcapsular space\u2192outer cortex\u2192deep cortex\u2192medullary sinus\u2192efferent lymphatics\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct sequence. This allows for systematic immune surveillance as the lymph passes through different functional zones of the node.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAfferent lymphatics\u2192subcapsular space\u2192deep cortex\u2192outer cortex\u2192medullary sinus\u2192efferent lymphatics\u003C/strong\u003E places the deep cortex before the outer cortex, but the outer cortex (containing B cell follicles) must be encountered before the deep cortex (containing T cells). \u003Cstrong\u003EAfferent lymphatics\u2192medullary sinus\u2192deep cortex\u2192outer cortex\u2192subcapsular space\u2192efferent lymphatics\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EAfferent lymphatics\u2192medullary sinus\u2192outer cortex\u2192deep cortex\u2192subcapsular space\u2192efferent lymphatics\u003C/strong\u003E both incorrectly begin with the medullary sinus rather than the subcapsular space, which is the initial receiving area for incoming lymph. \u003Cstrong\u003EAfferent lymphatics\u2192subcapsular space\u2192medullary sinus\u2192outer cortex\u2192deep cortex\u2192efferent lymphatics\u003C/strong\u003E bypasses the important immune surveillance function of the cortical regions by directing lymph straight to the medullary sinus. This organised flow pattern ensures that lymph fluid is systematically exposed to both B and T lymphocytes, maximising the opportunity for immune recognition and response.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Lymph flows through lymph nodes in a specific sequence: afferent vessels \u2192 subcapsular space \u2192 outer cortex \u2192 deep cortex \u2192 medullary sinus \u2192 efferent vessels","The outer cortex contains B cell follicles while the deep cortex (paracortex) contains T cells","This organised structure allows for efficient immune surveillance of lymph fluid"],"references":["Bona, C. A., \u0026 Bonilla, F. A. (2019). Textbook of immunology. CRC press.","Null M, Arbor TC, Agarwal M. Anatomy, Lymphatic System. 2023 Mar 6. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30020619.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97419"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14969"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97419"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T16:54:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T16:54:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7657"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115416"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships